JOHANNESBURG - Five unions, representing striking bus drivers, have come up with a counter offer to end the protracted wage talks. They’re asking for a 9 percent increase in the first year, and 8 percent in the second year. READ: Bus strike update: Unions meet to discuss way forward Employers say they've not received the offer yet. The bargaining council is suggesting an increase of 8.75 percent for year one, and 8.25 percent in year two. Bus companies were expected to meet on Tuesday. Workers slammed the brakes on bus services about three weeks ago, originally demanding a 12 percent wage hike. eNCA